verbose_text: The higher expression of ATP5L in male elephants compared to female (XREF_TABLE) may be attributable to the marked sexual dimorphism in size between male and female elephants, with males (average weight 4,100 -5,000 kg; average height 2.7-3.2 m at the shoulder) being significantly larger than females (average weight 2,300 -4,000 kg; average height 2.3-2.7 m at the shoulder) XREF_BIBR, and consequent differences likely in energy expenditure.
